<subSubSection id="18CC6B35D2CE5C91A51213A99B1435E4" pageId="16" pageNumber="309" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="A1ECB380D1C11EDB4649CC6D1974E6FA" pageId="16" pageNumber="309">
<taxonomicName id="FFF843EAB57D207E73D59D5F3B6955FF" LSID="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:7C83B2CC-BD8F-4BDA-A19D-E61110619770" authority="Grimaldi &amp; Cumming" authorityName="Grimaldi &amp; Cumming" authorityYear="2011" class="Insecta" family="Acroceridae" genus="Microburmyia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Microburmyia" order="Diptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="309" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Microburmyia Grimaldi &amp; Cumming</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="9075967FA271E2DDB20D711BFA4BEFFF" pageId="16" pageNumber="309">gen. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D5B970E1C84A4BBA2A86833F7B809AB7" pageId="16" pageNumber="309" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="9C1A907A3C6D650BAE87ED52AF9FE784" pageId="16" pageNumber="309">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CD627B2C0F969EC8E9F9CDAC0E7D18D8" pageId="16" pageNumber="309">R1 long, apex reaching to 2/3 length of wing; R1 branching off of the stem of R quite distad, R2+3 long, branching off of Rs in the distal half of the wing; cells br and bm large, length nearly half that of wing; M1+2 forked; vein A1 either incomplete or absent. Mesoscutum strongly arched; it and abdominal tergites devoid of bristle-like setae or long pilosity; apical tibial spurs lacking. Body size minute, ca. 1.0 mm in length.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="17E3D1FBB788D2DAD24B013AF6F10A43" pageId="16" pageNumber="309" type="type species">
<paragraph id="B7981CD386F371B1D473D0ADBF37AB1A" pageId="16" pageNumber="309">Type Species.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0A395C6C2B90422CB85B9249DE02A2E7" pageId="16" pageNumber="309">
<taxonomicName id="93460F36276A31DE7EC38D3CC1453CB2" authority="Grimaldi &amp; Cumming, 2011" authorityName="Grimaldi &amp; Cumming" authorityYear="2011" class="Insecta" family="Acroceridae" genus="Microburmyia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Microburmyia analvena" order="Diptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="309" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="analvena">Microburmyia analvena</taxonomicName>
, sp. n. By present designation
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="550196637A68F29ABE9BAB8D27B1F61F" pageId="16" pageNumber="309" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="A3652800F0FB625D46CBC7A311E14F62" pageId="16" pageNumber="309">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D606BB20CD11FA8B0976A25EA045B8FC" pageId="16" pageNumber="309">Derived from micro- (L.), minute; -burm-, Burma; and -myia (Gr.), fly, in reference to the minute body size and provenance of this brachyceran. Feminine.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="7DEC9B22BE2AC37A95ABCEBB72B3BC5B" lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="310" pageId="16" pageNumber="309" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="04648F035DB28955A48C201F5EB8BC45" pageId="16" pageNumber="309">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D7B9C1CBA4854F577EEB68209199EA17" lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="310" pageId="16" pageNumber="309">
The family placement of the two new species in this genus is not entirely certain, particularly since in mythicomyiids vein R2+3 is typically short and its apex fused with R1. The genus is placed in the 
<taxonomicName id="8AF2D9090EA83E51405890F473024CD9" family="Mythicomyiidae" lsidName="" pageId="16" pageNumber="309" rank="family">Mythicomyiidae</taxonomicName>
since the venation bears a resemblance to the Baltic amber genus 
<taxonomicName id="8D77E66562368B8B3CA6616CDD74F72C" authority="Evenhuis, 2002" authorityName="Evenhuis" authorityYear="2002" class="Insecta" family="Mythicomyiidae" genus="Carmenelectra" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Carmenelectra" order="Diptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="309" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Carmenelectra</taxonomicName>
Evenhuis (
<bibRefCitation id="5FAD21454E8714F80CDE7780815FC901" author="Evenhuis, NL" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="31" pageNumber="324" pagination="1 - 15" title="Review of the Tertiary microbombyliids (Diptera: Mythicomyiidae) in Baltic, Bitterfeld, and Dominican amber." volume="100" year="2002">Evenhuis 2002</bibRefCitation>
), though differing from that Baltic amber genus by R1 branching off of the stem of R quite distad (vs. near the base of the wing), R2+3 branching off of Rs in the distal half of the wing (vs. in the basal half), and by crossveins r-m and cu-m being in line (vs. stepped). Other features of 
<taxonomicName id="698B95895883AFB808B2467587F15A2E" authority="Grimaldi &amp; Cumming, 2011" authorityName="Grimaldi &amp; Cumming" authorityYear="2011" class="Insecta" family="Acroceridae" genus="Microburmyia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Microburmyia" order="Diptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="309" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Microburmyia</taxonomicName>
that are consistent with mythicomyiids are the strongly arched scutum, structure of apical antennal articles (with minute stylus 
<pageBreakToken id="D81E3457C92D65FA31532597CA9DEACF" pageId="17" pageNumber="310" start="start">in</pageBreakToken>
<taxonomicName id="2700F40093612125D2CDBC8334507684" authority="Grimaldi &amp; Cumming, 2011" authorityName="Grimaldi &amp; Cumming" authorityYear="2011" class="Insecta" family="Acroceridae" genus="Microburmyia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Microburmyia analvena" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="310" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="analvena">Microburmyia analvena</taxonomicName>
, ovoid first flagellomere in 
<taxonomicName id="3AC8EBEE65C67D5D60C75A0421634777" authority="Grimaldi &amp; Cumming, 2011" authorityName="Grimaldi &amp; Cumming" authorityYear="2011" class="Insecta" family="Acroceridae" genus="Microburmyia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Microburmyia veanalvena" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="310" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="veanalvena">Microburmyia veanalvena</taxonomicName>
), incomplete Sc vein, palpi minute or absent, and the minute body size. 
<taxonomicName id="316C99B85DF7C35A53C3028BD333A644" authority="Grimaldi &amp; Cumming, 2011" authorityName="Grimaldi &amp; Cumming" authorityYear="2011" class="Insecta" family="Acroceridae" genus="Microburmyia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Microburmyia" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="310" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Microburmyia</taxonomicName>
is plesiomorphic with respect to all other known mythicomyiids (cf., 
<bibRefCitation id="4D92BC3811D945920BCE43364C7E83A7" author="Evenhuis, NL" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="31" pageNumber="324" pagination="1 - 15" title="Review of the Tertiary microbombyliids (Diptera: Mythicomyiidae) in Baltic, Bitterfeld, and Dominican amber." volume="100" year="2002">Evenhuis 2002</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A1DF71C1E42C9DB9FD9D166A2B64390C" pageId="17" pageNumber="310">
<taxonomicName id="612E8663D94F8792AF2C67055629BCE5" family="Mythicomyiidae" lsidName="" pageId="17" pageNumber="310" rank="family">Mythicomyiidae</taxonomicName>
are traditionally (e.g., 
<bibRefCitation id="F8C81F466131561848C5FF1F8FA1E7DE" pageId="17" pageNumber="310">Hall 1981</bibRefCitation>
) and phylogenetically (e.g., 
<bibRefCitation id="59853015CB803FF7BF80EF654857A7E4" pageId="17" pageNumber="310">Yeates 1994</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="14E567855B08005BDE36BC0241643DF8" pageId="17" pageNumber="310">Woodley 1989</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="33207FE52D3E8915B1EADC22D5FEE3E2" pageId="17" pageNumber="310">Woodley et al. 2009</bibRefCitation>
) placed as the sister group to the 
<taxonomicName id="E72720CC6B11C30F1EA1590300B276AE" family="Bombyliidae" lsidName="" pageId="17" pageNumber="310" rank="family">Bombyliidae</taxonomicName>
s.s, often classified as a subfamily, but also as a separate family (e.g., 
<bibRefCitation id="8596BED677DA9A18A1B7999D71600301" author="Evenhuis, NL" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="31" pageNumber="324" pagination="1 - 15" title="Review of the Tertiary microbombyliids (Diptera: Mythicomyiidae) in Baltic, Bitterfeld, and Dominican amber." volume="100" year="2002">Evenhuis 2002</bibRefCitation>
). There is strong morphological and molecular support for 
<taxonomicName id="63A026741393D102869BA7E048DD5044" family="Bombyliidae" lsidName="" pageId="17" pageNumber="310" rank="family">Bombyliidae</taxonomicName>
+ 
<taxonomicName id="82EE9ED2A5325B17130D7C814F55C79F" family="Mythicomyiidae" lsidName="" pageId="17" pageNumber="310" rank="family">Mythicomyiidae</taxonomicName>
being the sister group to the rest of 
<taxonomicName id="2F6CD1D4224637DE6FC41E60BA5653CA" authority="Latreille, 1802" authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" class="Anthozoa" family="Thalassianthidae" genus="Asiloidea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Asiloidea" order="Actiniaria" pageId="17" pageNumber="310" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">Asiloidea</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="F411E62148BA0E365292A27FD79716B3" pageId="17" pageNumber="310">Woodley 1989</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="8B9978441FDC03C4AEF3598E317211F5" author="Yeates, DK" journalOrPublisher="Zoologica Scripta" pageId="34" pageNumber="327" pagination="105 - 121" title="Relationships of extant lower Brachycera (Diptera): a quantitative synthesis of morphological characters." url="doi: 10.1046/j.0300-3256.2001.00077.x" volume="31" year="2002">Yeates 2002</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="B22F5FE6F5878DB8F218B80A020A1F25" author="Wiegmann, BM" journalOrPublisher="Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, USA" pageId="34" pageNumber="327" pagination="5690 - 5695" title="Episodic radiations in the fly tree of life." volume="108" year="2011">Wiegmann et al. 2011</bibRefCitation>
) or the sister group to the rest of 
<taxonomicName id="FD146E114C8E37E48F5EC5F20A34D4F6" authority="Latreille, 1802" authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" class="Anthozoa" family="Thalassianthidae" genus="Asiloidea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Asiloidea" order="Actiniaria" pageId="17" pageNumber="310" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">Asiloidea</taxonomicName>
and Eremoneura (
<bibRefCitation id="1D2D919771569F22E244230E21053629" author="Sinclair, BJ" journalOrPublisher="Entomologica Scandinavica" pageId="33" pageNumber="326" pagination="407 - 432" title="Homology and phylogenetic implications of male genitalia in Diptera - Lower Brachycera." url="doi: 10.1163/187631293X00190" volume="24" year="1994">Sinclair et al. 1994</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="31920E7AA9A31C18AAC7ECCB111C4759" author="Trautwein, MD" journalOrPublisher="Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution" pageId="33" pageNumber="326" pagination="918 - 930" title="A multigene phylogeny of the fly superfamily Asiloidea (Insecta): Taxon sampling and additional genes reveal the sister-group to all higher flies (Cyclorrhapha)." url="doi: 10.1016/j.ympev.2010.04.017" volume="56" year="2010">Trautwein et al. 2010</bibRefCitation>
). With the exception of an unforked R4+5 and short or vestigial anal vein in 
<taxonomicName id="0F0AB5793499DB4BA93D12AC989FE897" authority="Grimaldi &amp; Cumming, 2011" authorityName="Grimaldi &amp; Cumming" authorityYear="2011" class="Insecta" family="Acroceridae" genus="Microburmyia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Microburmyia" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="310" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Microburmyia</taxonomicName>
, it is very interesting that its venation is intermediate between that of the 
<taxonomicName id="A17948A68FF85F811EA2E64BA0EB8FDC" family="Hilarimorphidae" lsidName="" pageId="17" pageNumber="310" rank="family">Hilarimorphidae</taxonomicName>
and the more specialized venation of mythicomyiines. This would lend support to the hypothesis that 
<taxonomicName id="CC4C7A17B780AB7F3653F3F402F7C14A" family="Hilarimorphidae" lsidName="" pageId="17" pageNumber="310" rank="family">Hilarimorphidae</taxonomicName>
is the sister group to the 
<taxonomicName id="6ECC31A5539390199E4470CD6D6F6249" family="Bombyliidae" lsidName="" pageId="17" pageNumber="310" rank="family">Bombyliidae</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="716D06C10C04DB93D2A7CB9C417D4472" pageId="17" pageNumber="310">Woodley 1989</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="01111B6274216757E2072D147B4E8550" pageId="17" pageNumber="310">Yeates 1994</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="5D3CC4FF44EC4101AED8F4BFFB419FF6" pageId="17" pageNumber="310">Woodley et al. 2009</bibRefCitation>
). Another hypothesis places the 
<taxonomicName id="DE40B0A4DA896BC0F37A7F7EC4D24D65" family="Hilarimorphidae" lsidName="" pageId="17" pageNumber="310" rank="family">Hilarimorphidae</taxonomicName>
(sometimes including the enigmatic and monotypic genus 
<taxonomicName id="18536F1229E0F7048DAEC493083690CA" class="Insecta" family="Apystomyiidae" genus="Apystomyia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Apystomyia" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="310" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Apystomyia</taxonomicName>
Melander 1950) as the sister group to the Eremoneura (Yeates, 2002) (see also discussion under 
<taxonomicName id="40A99602A3746789D68696480BAC8C92" family="Apystomyidae" lsidName="" pageId="17" pageNumber="310" rank="family">Apystomyidae</taxonomicName>
, vide infra). Oddly, the recent total-evidence phylogeny of flies placed the 
<taxonomicName id="3976E369B86BAFAE0BC093254981FD49" family="Hilarimorphidae" lsidName="" pageId="17" pageNumber="310" rank="family">Hilarimorphidae</taxonomicName>
(excluding 
<taxonomicName id="E9E30FE1F6D234290F9C14BE57C67758" class="Insecta" family="Apystomyiidae" genus="Apystomyia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Apystomyia" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="310" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Apystomyia</taxonomicName>
) as sister group to the 
<taxonomicName id="C7033D1DF2099A050422A9116EC1C48F" family="Acroceridae" lsidName="" pageId="17" pageNumber="310" rank="family">Acroceridae</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="B2AF2D6F6C6D5AFB86DCE37AA308FE87" author="Wiegmann, BM" journalOrPublisher="Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, USA" pageId="34" pageNumber="327" pagination="5690 - 5695" title="Episodic radiations in the fly tree of life." volume="108" year="2011">Wiegmann et al. 2011</bibRefCitation>
), for which there is very limited molecular and no morphological support, although this result does suggest a position of 
<taxonomicName id="955CB16B772F5D1C920B923E285942D5" family="Hilarimorphidae" lsidName="" pageId="17" pageNumber="310" rank="family">Hilarimorphidae</taxonomicName>
distant from Eremoneura.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="57E7F8967D690AD24841A5A032231E16" pageId="17" pageNumber="310">
Lastly, it is interesting to note that the fossil record of 
<taxonomicName id="224FB22E6F57A82E2F83559846BD0AC8" family="Bombyliidae" lsidName="" pageId="17" pageNumber="310" rank="family">Bombyliidae</taxonomicName>
s.s., exclusive of mythicomyiines, is entirely Tertiary. 
<taxonomicName id="04672B0082D6E294A0CA53121A5CA0FF" family="Bombyliidae" lsidName="" pageId="17" pageNumber="310" rank="family">Bombyliidae</taxonomicName>
is a large, cosmopolitan family (ca. 4,500 species) of flies that are most diverse in xeric ecosystems, where they are important pollinators of herbaceous plants. Their fossil record in sedimentary matrices and in amber (Baltic, Dominican) is quite diverse for North America and Europe (
<bibRefCitation id="6D7FD55A3E08D7B4710B11C846B653E6" pageId="17" pageNumber="310">Evenhuis 1994</bibRefCitation>
), suggesting that the bombyliids s.s. radiated rapidly in the early Tertiary.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
